  "prompt": "Is there any law in India to secretly report child labour?",
  "response": "Yes, in India, there are legal provisions to report child labour, and these can be done confidentially or anonymously if you wish. Here are the key details:\n\n### **Laws Against Child Labour**\n1. **Child Labour (Prohibition and Regulation) Amendment Act, 2016**:\n   - Prohibits the employment of children below the age of 14 in all occupations and processes.\n   - Adolescents (14-18 years) are prohibited from working in hazardous occupations and processes.\n\n2. **Right to Education Act, 2009**:\n   - Ensures free and compulsory education for children aged 6 to 14.\n\n3. **Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act, 2015**:\n   - Provides for the protection, care, and rehabilitation of children, including those engaged in child labour.\n\n### **How to Report Child Labour Secretly**\n1. **National Child Labour Project (NCLP) Helpline**:\n   - You can call the toll-free number **1098**, operated by Childline India Foundation. This helpline is available 24/7 and allows you to report cases of child labour anonymously.\n\n2. **Online Reporting**:\n   - You can file a complaint on the **Childline India website** (https://www.childlineindia.org) or through the **PENCIL Portal** (https://pencil.gov.in), which is specifically designed for reporting child labour cases. PENCIL (Platform for Effective Enforcement for No Child Labour) is an initiative by the Ministry of Labour and Employment.\n\n3. **Police**:\n   - You can also approach the local police station or dial **100** to report child labour anonymously.\n\n4. **NGOs and Activists**:\n   - Many NGOs work against child labour and can help you report cases while maintaining your confidentiality.\n\n### **Protection for Informers**\n- The law does not disclose the identity of the complainant unless required by a court order. You can report child labour without fear of retaliation.\n\n### **What Happens After Reporting**\n- Authorities investigate the complaint and take action, including rescuing the child, providing rehabilitation, and penalizing the employer.\n\nIf you witness child labour, you are encouraged to report it to ensure the child\u2019s safety and well-being.",
